00:14:19.990 --> 00:14:23.380
and they are a
considerable reason

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:27.640
for what we saw in the
incarceration crisis.

00:14:27.640 --> 00:14:30.910
And there are a lot of problems
with mandatory minimums,

00:14:30.910 --> 00:14:34.570
but in this case, in
like this spectrum,

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:38.600
they do raise the
certainty of punishment,

00:14:38.600 --> 00:14:45.550
but they have like a lot of
problems that would make us not

00:14:45.550 --> 00:14:46.840
want to use them.

00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:52.210
Like one thing, they
promote guilty pleas.

00:14:52.210 --> 00:14:55.010
So if I can, you know,
plea something else,

00:14:55.010 --> 00:14:58.070
even if I didn't do it, only to
escape the mandatory minimum,

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:00.910
I will do it, because
if I do go to court,

00:15:00.910 --> 00:15:03.490
I might get the
mandatory minimum,

00:15:03.490 --> 00:15:05.140
and there are a lot
of other problems

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:06.515
with mandatory
minimums, but they

00:15:06.515 --> 00:15:08.360
do solve this specific problem.

00:15:08.360 --> 00:15:08.920
Yeah?

00:15:08.920 --> 00:15:11.200
AUDIENCE: Are there
mandatory minimums in Israel.

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:12.075
AYELET OZ: There are.

00:15:12.075 --> 00:15:14.500
There are a few, actually,
like back a decade ago,

00:15:14.500 --> 00:15:15.850
there was this huge trend.

00:15:15.850 --> 00:15:18.280
Like everything got
mandatory minimums.

00:15:18.280 --> 00:15:20.080
But actually,
there's case law that

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:26.050
says that you can put the
mandatory minimum on like,

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:30.010
to be served only if
he does another crime,

00:15:30.010 --> 00:15:32.470
or as civil work.

00:15:32.470 --> 00:15:35.665
So there are all kinds of ways
that case law kind of like

00:15:35.665 --> 00:15:39.900
tried to move the
mandatory minimums around.

00:15:39.900 --> 00:15:42.310
So they are not as
harsh as in the US,

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:46.330
and actually, nowadays the
trend kind of went down,

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:49.480
I think a lot because of
the problem of guilty pleas,

00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:52.810
and because they saw that
mandatory minimums kind

00:15:52.810 --> 00:15:57.620
of distort the system and
the play between the parties.

00:15:57.620 --> 00:15:59.420
So now they don't
use it that much,

00:15:59.420 --> 00:16:00.670
although they could come back.

00:16:00.670 --> 00:16:03.190
Like it's a running
trend, we can call it.

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:10.210
But then, OK, a bit to what
this guy was saying, OK

00:16:10.210 --> 00:16:11.150
so what happened.

00:16:11.150 --> 00:16:13.420
OK, but we can't
stop sending people

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:16.270
to prison because the crime
rates will go off the roof.

00:16:16.270 --> 00:16:19.570
And here, we actually have
the really interesting example

00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:21.010
of Finland.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:24.800
And like just to put
Finland in perspective,

00:16:24.800 --> 00:16:30.670
this is more or less the
incarceration rate in Europe.

00:16:30.670 --> 00:16:34.930
So we have over here the
former Soviet Union, which

00:16:34.930 --> 00:16:38.170
uses incarceration quite a bit.

00:16:38.170 --> 00:16:40.700
This is Eastern
Europe, Western Europe,

00:16:40.700 --> 00:16:42.256
and these are the
Nordic countries.

00:16:42.256 --> 00:16:43.630
As you can see,
as we always say,

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:45.880
the Nordic counties
are really nice.

00:16:45.880 --> 00:16:47.120
They don't use prison a lot.

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:49.960
They just hug over there
all the time, you know.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:51.500
It's a really lovely
place to live.

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:53.720
So as you can see, all
the Nordic countries

00:16:53.720 --> 00:16:58.990
use prison in quite a low rate.

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:01.780
And they use a lot of
alternatives to incarceration.

00:17:01.780 --> 00:17:04.329
They actually have a
really nice system.

00:17:04.329 --> 00:17:10.480
But Finland was not as nice
as it went up until '90s.

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:14.470
So you could see, if we zoom
in on the Nordic countries,

00:17:14.470 --> 00:17:17.619
you could see that Finland
had in comparison quite

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:20.260
a large incarceration rate.

00:17:20.260 --> 00:17:25.839
So if they had somewhere
around 60 people per 1000,

00:17:25.839 --> 00:17:31.150
Finland had nearly 200
per 1,000 population,

00:17:31.150 --> 00:17:34.840
and then it had this
big prison reform,

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:40.270
and went down and became as nice
as the other Nordic countries.

00:17:40.270 --> 00:17:45.370
And you would expect, OK, if
we reduce by 2/3 our prison

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:48.272
population, OK, the crime
must go off the roof,

00:17:48.272 --> 00:17:50.170
right And what we
see is actually,

00:17:50.170 --> 00:17:52.510
there is an increase
in the crime

00:17:52.510 --> 00:17:58.000
rate in the Nordic countries
ever since the '50s to now,

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.750
but what we can see, Finland is
somewhere here in the middle,

00:18:01.750 --> 00:18:04.240
it does not jump up
more than everyone else.

00:18:04.240 --> 00:18:08.980
Like, it reduced its
prison population by 2/3,

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:12.640
but the rise in crime
was similar to all

00:18:12.640 --> 00:18:14.600
the other countries
who never had those.

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:20.200
So you can see, I think
it's a very strong example

00:18:20.200 --> 00:18:26.080
to show that there really
is no logical connection

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:29.640
between the use of the prison
sentence and the crime rate.

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:30.372
Yeah?

00:18:30.372 --> 00:18:37.820
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] the
number of prisoners [INAUDIBLE]

