00:22:35.960 --> 00:22:39.650
And now I want to stop
talking about international

00:22:39.650 --> 00:22:43.340
comparisons, and now
I want to give you

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:47.060
a bit of who are the
people in prison in Israel.

00:22:47.060 --> 00:22:49.820
Like when you think of people
in prison, what you usually

00:22:49.820 --> 00:22:55.040
think about are
the sex felonies,

00:22:55.040 --> 00:22:57.980
you think about, our
nice armed robber, you

00:22:57.980 --> 00:22:59.360
think about homicide.

00:22:59.360 --> 00:23:01.400
But the vast
majority of prisoners

00:23:01.400 --> 00:23:04.100
are actually in very
short prison sentences.

00:23:04.100 --> 00:23:07.820
So as you can see--

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:11.000
I thought I had
the numbers, but I

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.830
think the common number is
that about 75% of prisoners

00:23:15.830 --> 00:23:19.880
are up to two years in
prison, and everybody else

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:22.520
are in the long tail.

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:26.120
So when we talk about
the use of prison,

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:33.920
we usually imagine those
very serious felonies,

00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:36.780
but the people who are
actually going into prison

00:23:36.780 --> 00:23:42.950
are most of the time for
medium range felonies.

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:44.630
So if it's a really
low felony, you

00:23:44.630 --> 00:23:46.770
will usually not go to prison.

00:23:46.770 --> 00:23:49.820
But kind of like
the medium range

00:23:49.820 --> 00:23:53.480
is the vast majority of people
in prison who just change.

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:58.130
So one problem with
the prison sentence

00:23:58.130 --> 00:24:03.140
is that it has what we call the
criminogenic effect, meaning

00:24:03.140 --> 00:24:08.390
if there's one thing that will
determine if someone will go

00:24:08.390 --> 00:24:12.080
to prison again, yes or not, is
the question, was he in prison

00:24:12.080 --> 00:24:12.840
before.

00:24:12.840 --> 00:24:18.410
People who were in prison
to a vastly larger ratio

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:23.060
go back to prison, and
there are a few explanations

00:24:23.060 --> 00:24:26.060
to why this is
happening, one of which

00:24:26.060 --> 00:24:28.300
is that people are getting
accustomed to prison,

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.920
meaning once you've been
to prison for, let's say,

00:24:30.920 --> 00:24:35.030
six months, you're not as scared
of it as people who come out.

00:24:35.030 --> 00:24:38.690
We actually have this really
big problem with minors,

00:24:38.690 --> 00:24:41.630
meaning a minor who was
arrested, for the first three

00:24:41.630 --> 00:24:45.530
days, let's say two weeks,
he will do everything

00:24:45.530 --> 00:24:46.940
to go out of prison.

00:24:46.940 --> 00:24:51.890
He will agree to go to
rehabilitation plans.

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:55.530
He will agree to take all
kind of restrictions and such.

00:24:55.530 --> 00:24:57.800
But after he's been like a
month and a half in prison,

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:00.710
oh, you know, you get
accustomed to stuff.

00:25:00.710 --> 00:25:03.950
And prison, actually, you
know, you could live in there.

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:06.750
No one is asking
you to do anything,

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:09.810
you've got your friends,
and OK, well, I'm

00:25:09.810 --> 00:25:11.930
not going to go to rehab now.

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:13.670
Rehab is hard.

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:16.910
And it's actually a great
problem with minors, but also

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:18.300
with adults.

00:25:18.300 --> 00:25:22.730
People get accustomed to
prison, and in prison they

00:25:22.730 --> 00:25:26.930
get a network of other
people who are criminals,

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:30.710
and many times they
get disconnected

00:25:30.710 --> 00:25:36.800
from the previous environment,
from the previous community,

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:38.930
and this is the only
community they know.

00:25:38.930 --> 00:25:42.020
They have a really
hard time going back

00:25:42.020 --> 00:25:46.790
to society in regards
to work, to employment,

00:25:46.790 --> 00:25:48.410
to finding an apartment.

00:25:48.410 --> 00:25:50.180
So all of these
things actually do

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:51.600
what we call the rotating door.

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:55.280
They put people back to
prison basically because they

00:25:55.280 --> 00:25:59.090
have nothing else to look for
outside once they're going out

00:25:59.090 --> 00:26:00.200
of prison.

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:04.130
So we do have a really
important mission

00:26:04.130 --> 00:26:09.140
to try to prevent those
short time sentences,

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:12.440
because I think we can all agree
that if someone, I don't know,

00:26:12.440 --> 00:26:16.100
raped a woman, he
should be in prison.

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:19.935
Actually, like in most
cases, it won't be debatable.

00:26:19.935 --> 00:26:21.870
AUDIENCE: So what crimes
are we talking about?

00:26:21.870 --> 00:26:29.830
AYELET OZ: We're talking about
breaking into apartments,

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:31.700
like in small numbers.

00:26:31.700 --> 00:26:37.160
We're talking about
drug felonies.

00:26:37.160 --> 00:26:43.430
We're talking about battery and
assault in a really low key.

00:26:43.430 --> 00:26:46.690
We're talking about
slightly larger theft.

00:26:46.690 --> 00:26:49.730
So this is like really
low violence act

00:26:49.730 --> 00:26:56.030
or mediocre property felonies,
basically, and drug felonies.

00:26:56.030 --> 00:26:56.530
Yeah?

00:26:56.530 --> 00:27:00.475
AUDIENCE: Isn't like just
the fact of getting convicted

00:27:00.475 --> 00:27:02.170
enough to put you
into this cycle,

00:27:02.170 --> 00:27:04.610
even without going to prison?

00:27:04.610 --> 00:27:06.480
AYELET OZ: No, not
to the same extent.

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:09.230
I mean, yes, and we'll
talk about alternatives

00:27:09.230 --> 00:27:11.720
to the criminal process.

00:27:11.720 --> 00:27:15.930
There is some problem
when you get convicted.

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:19.820
So it has some of these effects,
but the effects of taking you

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:24.140
out of the community, of
isolating you, and making you

00:27:24.140 --> 00:27:27.350
like recreate your
sense of identity,

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:29.270
this happens to a
large extent in prison

00:27:29.270 --> 00:27:31.700
and will not happen if you
still live with your family,

00:27:31.700 --> 00:27:34.650
if you still go to work
and all these things.

00:27:34.650 --> 00:27:37.750
So the concept of
isolating you is

00:27:37.750 --> 00:27:42.520
one of the harsher
effects of prison.

00:27:42.520 --> 00:27:46.460
Like this is the huge
amount of the punishment,

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:50.770
and it's also the one
thing that has the most

00:27:50.770 --> 00:27:54.100
effect on what happens next.

00:27:54.100 --> 00:27:58.390
So actually, yeah, so
I'm going to go back

00:27:58.390 --> 00:28:00.920
to the money in a second.

00:28:00.920 --> 00:28:04.600
So there was actually this
very important committee,

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:11.749
you said, in 2015, led by the
Supreme Justice Dalia Dorner.

00:28:11.749 --> 00:28:13.540
And this why it's called
the Dorner report.

00:28:13.540 --> 00:28:17.500
And it actually tried to
rethink criminal justice

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:21.040
policy in Israel, and unlike
most of these committees,

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:24.250
this actually like
really got implemented

00:28:24.250 --> 00:28:26.470
in government decision.

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:29.290
Now they are following
reports on how

00:28:29.290 --> 00:28:31.490
everything should change.

00:28:31.490 --> 00:28:34.660
But it really had
its wave, and it's

00:28:34.660 --> 00:28:37.730
something that is very real
in criminal justice today.

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:40.180
It's not something like,
OK, let's take our report,

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:42.580
put it in a nice
drawer and carry on

00:28:42.580 --> 00:28:46.000
with our lives, which is usually
happening with such reports.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:52.220
